docs.abstract: In the new Amazon show “Jean-Claude Van Johnson,” the seemingly washed-up Muscles from Brussels gleefully sends up his action star image.
docs.snippet: In the new Amazon show “Jean-Claude Van Johnson,” the seemingly washed-up Muscles from Brussels gleefully sends up his action star image.
docs.lead_paragraph: SIMI VALLEY, Calif. — On a recent afternoon on his expansive estate here, in a beautifully appointed living room the size of a mead hall, Jean-Claude Van Damme suddenly fired a high kick at my face, stopping short of crunching cartilage and bone. I didn’t ask him to do it, but it was a thrill nonetheless. After all, he’s aimed that very same foot at the heads of action superstars like Dolph Lundgren, Bolo Yeung and Sylvester Stallone.

headline.main: Jean-Claude Van Damme Plays Jean-Claude Van Damme, for Kicks

docs.lead_paragraph: In recent months Amazon has articulated a new original-content strategy: go “Game of Thrones” or go home. It wants “big shows,” genre dramas with automatic fan appeal, and it’s signed up creators like the film director Wong Kar-wai and the “Walking Dead” impresario Robert Kirkman to provide them.

headline.main: Review: Amazon’s New Pilots, the End of an Era?

docs.abstract: Technologists once told us that social bots would change our lives forever. They were right — but not in the way they expected.
docs.snippet: Technologists once told us that social bots would change our lives forever. They were right — but not in the way they expected.
docs.lead_paragraph: In 2016, restless tech-industry forecasters enjoyed a rare moment of consensus: Whatever else might be coming next, everyone seemed to agree that bots would be a big part of it. The analyst Benedict Evans, in a representative essay, located a promising future specifically in chat bots — conversational interfaces for artificial intelligence, designed to assist with particular tasks. Facebook, the year before, created a personal-assistant chat bot, and the company would soon open its Messenger app up to outside developers, who it hoped would create more bots to help people shop, look things up or otherwise organize their lives. Amazon’s Echo, by then already a surprise mainstream success, provided a tailwind: Here was a widely used artificial intelligence just sitting there on millions of countertops.

headline.main: Not the Bots We Were Looking For
headline.print_headline: Not the Bots We Were Looking For
